A transient fictitious stress boundary element method for porothermoelastic media


A. Ghassemi*, Q. Zhang

Department of Geology and Geological Engineering, University of North Dakota, Box 8358, Grand Forks, ND 58202, USA

Received 12 August 2003; revised 28 December 2003; accepted 25 May 2004

Available online 24 August 2004

Abstract


The development of an indirect transient boundary element method for porothermoelastic media is described. Specifically, the fictitious stress method is extended to non-isothermal poroelasticity to solve coupled porothermoelastic problems. The fundamental solutions and numerical procedures are described and an application is presented. In particular, the model is used to study the stress and pore pressure distributions around a wellbore drilled in hot rock. There is good agreement between the numerical predictions and analytical results. The analysis is useful for determining the conditions for wellbore failure while drilling as well as for calculating the classical fracture initiation pressure for hydraulic fracturing. The results indicate that the transient formulation of the fictitious stress method is an accurate and suitable means for solving problems in porothermoelasticity. (C) 2004 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.

Keywords: Fictitious stress; Hydraulic fracture; Point heat source; Pore pressure; Poroelasticity; Porothermoelasticity; Wellbore failure

1. Introduction


Coupled thermal and poromechanical processes play an important role in a number of problems of interest in geomechanics such as stability of boreholes and hydraulic fracturing in geothermal reservoirs or high temperature petroleum bearing formations. This is due to that fact that when rocks are heated/cooled, the bulk solid as well as the pore fluid tend to undergo expansion/contraction. A volumetric expansion can result in significant pressurization of the pore fluid depending on the degree of containment and the thermal and hydraulic properties of the fluid as well as the solid. The net effect is a coupling of thermal and poromechanical processes. A few analytical procedures have been developed and used to solve geomechanics problems of interest involving coupled thermal and poromechanical problems [1-4]. However, many problems formulated within the framework of porothermoelasticity are not amenable to analytical treatment and need to be solved numerically. The boundary element techniques have been successfully applied to many geological engineering problems [5-8]. The boundary element method (BEM) or the boundary integral equation formulation also has proven effective for the poroelastic and thermoelastic problems [6,9,10] . The direct and the indirect BEMs for poroelasticity have been presented in Refs. [10-13]. Also, a direct method for porothermoelasticity in the Laplace transform domain has been presented in Ref. [14]. This paper presents a transient indirect BEM for porothermoelastic isotropic material. An overview of porothermoelasticity is presented first. Then, the reciprocal theorem is used to derive the Somigliana integrals in the time domain, leading to the integral equations for the fictitious stress method [5].

2. Equations of porothermoelasticity


The theory of poroelasticity couples pore pressure and solid stress fields in deformable fluid saturated porous rocks [15]. In the isothermal poroelastic theory, the time-dependent fluid flow is incorporated by combining the fluid mass conservation with Darcy's law; and the basic constitutive equations relate the total stress to both the effective stress, given by deformation of the rock matrix, and the fluid pore pressure. Thermally induced pore pressure and stresses play an important role in many geomechanics problems such as reservoir stimulation by hydraulic fracturing and borehole stability in high-temperature rocks. A thermoelastic approach combines the theory of heat conduction with the elastic constitutive equations, thus coupling the temperature and stress fields. In order to consider the influence of a temperature gradient on both pore pressure and stresses, it is necessary to use a non-isothermal poroelastic theory, or porothermoelasticity. The governing equations of porothermoelasticity are [16-20] as follows.

where σij denotes the components of the total stress tensor, ζ is the variation of the fluid content per unit reference volume of the porous material,and εij are the components of the strain tensor related to the solid displacements ui by εij=12(ui,j+uj,i).wi and hi represent the volume of the fluid and the amount of heat flow per unit surface area in the i -direction,respectively. γ and ϑ represent a fluid and a heat source intensity, and their integration over time yields the source strengths given by Q and Λ ,respectively. The constant K is the rock’s bulk modulus; B is Skempton’s pore pressure coefficient; α=3(vu−v)/B(1−2v)(1+vu) is Biot’s effective stress coefficient; βs′ is the volumetric thermal expansion coefficient of the bulk solid under constant pore pressure and stress; and β′′s and βf represent the volumetric thermal expansion coefficients of the solid matrix and the pore fluid,respectively. The former, β′′s ,reflects the phenomena engendered by the internal pore geometry and stress fields that are caused by a temperature change [16]; it may be considered equal to β′s (henceforth denoted by βs ) if the change in temperature is not expected to change porosity, ϕo.κ=k/μ ,in which k is dynamic permeability and μ is the fluid viscosity; kT is the thermal conductivity and cT is the thermal diffusivity. ς=(ρC/T0)T denotes the entropy of the matrix per unit reference volume,in which T0 is the absolute temperature, ρ is the rock density,and C is the rock specific heat [17]. fi,fiT ,and Fi represent the solid fluid,and heat body forces, respectively.

Note that the convective heat transport is neglected in the heat flow equation. This is justified for most rocks of interest as they are well represented by a low permeability system [1]. It should also be noted that for most rocks, heating/cooling produces thermal stresses and changes pore pressure, but stress and pressure changes do not significantly alter the temperature field [23] so that, the latter is not coupled to the equations for the pore pressure and solid displacements:

(13)Gui,jj+(G1−2v)uj,ji−αp,i−βsKT,i=−Fi,i

1M∂p∂t=kμp,jj−α∂εkk∂t+[αβs+ϕ(βf−βs)]∂T∂t

(14)+M(γ−κfi,i)

(15)∂T∂t=cTT,ii−cTfi,iT+1ρCϑ

in which G is the shear modulus and M=2G(vu−v)/α2 (1−2ν)(1−2νu) is Biot’s modulus.

3. Transient porothermoelastic fictitious stress method


The fictitious stress method is an indirect BEM that is based on the analytic solution to the problem of point force and sources in an infinite elastic solid. It is a versatile method for solving geomechanics problems involving underground openings of arbitrary shape. Similarly to the case for poroelasticity [12], a rigorous derivation of the indirect formulation for porothermoelasticity begins with Betti's reciprocal theorem. Consider two independent states (starred and unstarred) of stress, pore pressure, and temperature along with the corresponding variation of strain, fluid content per unit reference volume, and entropy per unit volume. Then, the theory of reciprocity of work takes the form:


(16)σijεij∗+pζ∗+Tς∗=σij∗εij+p∗ζ+T∗ς

where ζ(=−wi,i) and ς represent the variation of fluid volume and entropy per unit reference volume, respectively. The work is expressed in the unit of energy/volume ≡ force/ area: [J/m3≡Pa] . Hence, ς maybe expressed in terms of [J/m3K]≡[Pa/K]∈T(K) in the SI system. The two states are at different spatial and temporal coordinates, so that one should write:

σij(χ,τ)εij∗(χ−x,t−τ)+p(χ,τ)ζ∗(χ−x,t−τ)

+T(χ,τ)ς∗(χ−x,t−τ)

=σij∗(χ−x,t−τ)εij(χ,τ)+p∗(χ−x,t−τ)ζ(χ,τ)

+T∗(χ−x,t−τ)ς(χ,τ)

Upon expressing εij in terms of ui and ζ in terms of wi ,the integration of the above relation over the problem domain, Ω , and time yields:

∫0t∫Γ[σijnjui∗−σij∗njui]dχdτ−∫0t∫Γ[pwi∗−p∗wi]dχdτ

−1T0∫0t∫Γ[Thi∗−T∗hi]dχdτ+∫0t∫Ω[Fiui∗−Fi∗ui]dχdτ

+∫0t∫Ω[fiwi∗−fi∗wi]dχdτ+1T0∫0t∫Ω[fiThi∗−fiT∗hi]dχdτ

+∫0t∫Ω(pQ∗−p∗Q)dχdτ+∫0t∫Ω(TΛ∗−T∗Λ)dχdτ

+∫0t∫Ω(pζ∗|τ=0−p∗ζ|τ=0)dχdτ

(17)+1T0∫0t∫Ω(Tς∗|τ=0−T∗ς|τ=0)dχdτ=0

It should be noted that the surface integrals were obtained using the divergence theorem, and the domain integrals were recast by utilizing Eqs. (5)-(11). Details of the mathematical procedures can be found for the similar case of poroelasticity in Ref. [22]. Then, the fundamental solutions for instantaneous point forces, fluid source, and heat source are substituted for the starred state body forces in the above equations. Following a procedure similar to poroelasticity [22] one obtains the following Somigliana type integral equations for solid displacements, pore pressure, and temperature, respectively:

4. Numerical implementation


The solution of the integral equations for the unknown fictitious forces and fluid/heat sources is achieved using a boundary collocation technique [6]. The problem boundary is divided into a number of elements(J)and the time is divided into a number of steps(S). Then,fictitious forces and fluid sources are distributed over each element in space and time using a desired shape functions such that the sum of their effects satisfies the prescribed conditions of zero tractions and pore pressures. It is assumed that the boundary elements are straight segments with collocation points located at the center of each element. The induced normal and shear stresses,pore pressure,and temperature at time t ,on element ’ M ’ due to a constant spatial distribution of continuous normal and shear forces and sources on element ’ N ’, occurring at time τ ,are given by:

σnnM(x,t)=[∑N=1J⁡σnnkcp(x,t′)ΔψkNr+σnncs(x,t′)ΔϕNr

(38)+σnnch(x,t′)ΔφNr]

σsnM(x,t)=[∑N=1J⁡σsnkcp(x,t′)ΔψkNr+σsncs(x,t′)ΔϕNr

(39)+σsnch(x,t′)ΔφNr]

pM(x,t)=[∑N=1J⁡pkcp(x,t′)ΔψkNr+pcs(x,t′)ΔϕNr

(40)+pch(x,t′)ΔφNr]

(41)TM(x,t)=[1T0∑N=1J⁡Tch(x,t′)ΔφNr]

The boundary influence coefficients such as σijkcp denote the actual stresses at the midpoint of element M due to a constant in time force applied to the element N in the k direction (at time τ ):

σijkcp(x,t−τ)=aiℵajm∑r=0S⁡∫τrt∫Γeipσℵmkip(x,t−τ)dΓedτ

(42)=aiℓajm∑r=0S⁡∫Γeipσℓmkip(x,t−τr)dΓe

Note that aiℓ is the rotation matrix from the influencing(N)to the influenced(M)element’s coordinate system (direction cosines). The integration with respect to time is carried out analytically using a continuous constant source approximation. The superscripts and ’ cp ’,’ cs ’ and ’ ch ’ refer to continuous force, continuous fluid source, and continuous heat source,respectively; and t′=t−τ . Because the time integral is performed by tracing back to the time origin for the solution at any given time, i.e. it is carried out in the convolutional sense, no internal discretization would be necessary. A constant time step is used and the new space integrals are performed analytically using the elemental expressions for continuous in time point force and point source solutions. The solutions for a heat source in a porothermoelastic medium [20] are integrated over a straight line segment (assuming a constant distribution) and are listed in the Appendix. In addition, existing analytic expressions for poroelasticity [11] as well as numerical integration are used where necessary.

5. Example


Consider a borehole with radius R=0.1m in a reservoir that is at a temperature of 200∘C (Fig. 2). The reservoir rock is assumed to be granite and saturated with water. The input parameters for water saturated Westerly Granite [19] are shown in Table 1. The wellbore wall is suddenly cooled by water and maintained at 80∘C . For clarity of presentation and isolation of the role of temperature, only thermally induced stress and pore pressures are studied. Thus, and pore pressure and stress loadings are not considered, meaning that the far field pore pressure and stresses are considered to be zero. The problem boundary conditions are:

(43)[ at r=R:Δσrr=−σrr∞Δσrθ=−σrθ∞Δp=−pΔT=−120][ at r→∞:σrr=0σrθ=0p=0T=200]


Fig. 2. Stress, pore pressure, and temperature boundary conditions for the wellbore.

Due to symmetry only a quarter of the wellbore is modeled using 10 elements (Fig. 3). For each computation, the time is divided into 10 steps with the value of increment adjusted accordingly.

Figs. 4-7 illustrate the profiles of temperature, induced pore pressure, induced tangential stress, and induced radial stress around the wellbore. Analytical results are also shown for comparison. As can be observed, the numerical results are in agreement with the analytic solution [3]. This demonstrates the validity of this numerical approach for the case of porothermoelastic problems under consideration.

Fig. 4 shows the transient temperature distribution; it is typical of a conductive heat transfer situation. The formation is gradually cooled off when the borehole temperature is suddenly reduced. Fig. 5 is the distribution of induced pore pressure; a pressure drop is generated near the borehole at early times. With time, the pore pressure peak is reduced and moves away from the well where it gradually reaches the original state. Fig. 6 presents the thermally induced tangential stress; cooling induces a significant tangential tensile stress around the wellbore. This is caused by the tendency of the rock to shrink near the borehole wall. Away from the borehole wall, the magnitude of the induced tensile stress decreases and changes its sign at some point inside the formation, i.e. turns into a compressive stress. This is because the shrinkage of the material near the borehole due to cooling tends to pull on the outer rock, inducing a compressive stress. The compressive zone gradually moves away from the borehole while its peak diminishes in magnitude. Fig. 7 illustrates the thermally induced radial stress; a significant radial tensile stress peak is produced inside the formation. At later times, the tensile stress zone moves inside the formation while the magnitude of its peak increases. These observations are consistent with the results in Ref. [3].

6. Discussion and conclusions


A transient fictitious stress BEM has been developed for solving plane strain problems in porothermoelasticity. Presently, only the problem of a vertical borehole with a circular cross-section is solved to demonstrate the validity of the porothermoelastic formulation and numerical implementation of the method. In the current implementation, we find that the transient formulation yields accurate results efficiently, using constant boundary elements. The results presented illustrate the importance of the role of temperature in wellbore failure and hydraulic fracture initiation. Cooling of the wellbore can lead to fracturing; it also increases the stress intensity at the fracture tip leading to crack growth, the latter will be further investigated in the future using the displacement discontinuity method. Similar to Ref. [10] the method can also be extended to complete plane strain [24] to allow treatment of inclined wellbores.
